Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Observations:¶

Cuisine Type: The most popular types are "American," "Japanese," "Italian," and "Chinese," which have the highest frequency. These cuisines dominate the dataset in terms of customer preferences.

Cost of the Order: The histogram confirms a right-skewed distribution, with most orders costing below 15 dollars, as shown by the boxplot and descriptive statistics (50th percentile or median is $14.14). This supports the observation that the majority of orders are on the lower cost spectrum.

Day of the Week: As expected, people tend to eat out more on weekends, which is reflected in the count plot for the day of the week, showing a higher frequency of orders on weekends compared to weekdays.

Ratings: The highest frequency of ratings is "Not given," followed by 5, 4, and 3. This suggests that many customers don't leave ratings, but when they do, they tend to give positive feedback (5 being the most common numeric rating).

Food Preparation Time: Based on the descriptive statistics, the mean preparation time is 27.37 minutes, and the median is 27 minutes. This confirms a very slight right skew, which aligns with your observation. The preparation times appear to be updated in 5-minute increments, as the histogram shows peaks at these intervals (20, 25, 30 minutes).

Delivery Time: The mean delivery time is 24.16 minutes, and the median is 25 minutes. The slight left skew observed is confirmed by the small difference between the mean and median, suggesting that delivery times are close to normally distributed but centered around 25 minutes.

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer¶

In [124]:
# Convert the 'rating' column to numeric, treating 'Not given' as NaN
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Group the data by restaurant and calculate the number of ratings and the average rating
restaurant_ratings = df.groupby('restaurant_name').agg(
    rating_count=('rating', 'count'),
    average_rating=('rating', 'mean')
)

# Filter the restaurants that fulfill the conditions: rating count > 50 and average rating > 4
promotional_offer_restaurants = restaurant_ratings[
    (restaurant_ratings['rating_count'] > 50) &
    (restaurant_ratings['average_rating'] > 4)
]

# Display the restaurants that fulfill the criteria
promotional_offer_restaurants

These restaurants should be highlighted in advertisements as they are not only popular but also well-loved by their customers. Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders¶

In [125]:
# Define a function to calculate revenue based on cost of order
def calculate_revenue(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

# Apply the function to each order and calculate revenue
df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_revenue)

# Calculate the total net revenue generated by the company
net_revenue = df['revenue'].sum()

net_revenue
Out[125]:
6166.303

Observations: The company has generated a total of $6,166.30 from all orders. The total net revenue provides insight into the company’s current revenue performance. By analyzing how the distribution of orders (small, medium, and large) contributes to the overall revenue, the company can identify key areas for growth, such as expanding partnerships with restaurants that generate higher-order values.¶

Observations:¶

Weekdays: The average delivery time is approximately 28.34 minutes.

Weekends: The average delivery time is significantly shorter, around 22.47 minutes.

Delivery Time Differences: There is a noticeable difference in delivery times between weekdays and weekends. The shorter delivery times on weekends could be attributed to several factors:

Lower traffic congestion: During weekends, roads may be less busy, allowing delivery personnel to reach their destinations faster.

Operational efficiency: Restaurants and delivery services may have better planning and more resources allocated during peak weekend times to handle the higher order volume more efficiently.

Impact on Customer Satisfaction: Faster delivery times during weekends might contribute to higher customer satisfaction on those days. The company could leverage this insight by advertising faster delivery times as a weekend feature to attract more customers during those days.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations)¶

Conclusions¶

  1. Customer Preferences

    • Cuisine Popularity:
      • American cuisine is the most ordered, accounting for a significant portion of orders, especially on weekends.
      • Other popular cuisines include Japanese, Italian, and Chinese, indicating diverse customer tastes.
    • Ordering Patterns:
      • Higher order volumes are observed during weekends, suggesting increased demand when customers have more leisure time.

  2. Order Costs and Revenue

    • Order Value Distribution:
      • While the majority of orders are under 15 USD, approximately 29.24% of orders exceed 20 USD.
      • Higher-value orders contribute disproportionately to the company's net revenue.
    • Revenue Generation:
      • The company generated a total net revenue of 6,166.30 USD, with higher commissions from orders over 20 USD.

  3. Customer Ratings and Feedback

    • Engagement Levels:
      • A substantial number of orders (38.78%) are not rated, indicating low engagement in providing feedback.
    • Satisfaction Indicators:
      • Among rated orders, the majority are positive (ratings of 4 and 5), reflecting overall customer satisfaction.
    • Restaurant Performance:
      • The Meatball Shop has the highest average rating (4.31) among restaurants with more than 50 ratings.
      • Shake Shack has the highest order volume but a slightly lower average rating (4.16).

  4. Operational Efficiency

    • Delivery Times:
      • The average delivery time is longer on weekdays (28.34 minutes) compared to weekends (22.47 minutes).
      • Approximately 10.54% of orders take more than 60 minutes from order placement to delivery, potentially affecting customer satisfaction.

Recommendations¶

  1. Optimize Weekday Operations

    • Improve Delivery Efficiency:
      • Analyze delivery logistics to reduce delivery times on weekdays.
      • Implement route optimization and increase staffing during peak weekday hours.
    • Enhance Restaurant Coordination:
      • Work closely with restaurants to streamline food preparation processes during weekdays.

  2. Boost Customer Engagement

    • Increase Ratings Participation:
      • Introduce incentives such as discounts or loyalty points for customers who provide ratings and feedback.
      • Simplify the rating process within the app to encourage more participation.
    • Leverage Feedback:
      • Use customer feedback to identify areas for improvement and to recognize high-performing restaurants and delivery personnel.

  3. Strategic Marketing Initiatives

    • Promote High-Rated Restaurants:
      • Feature top-rated restaurants like The Meatball Shop and Blue Ribbon Sushi in promotions to attract customers seeking quality experiences.
    • Cuisine-Based Campaigns:
      • Develop marketing campaigns highlighting popular cuisines, especially American cuisine on weekends.

  4. Increase High-Value Orders

    • Upselling and Bundling:
      • Encourage customers to increase order value through bundle deals or add-on suggestions during the ordering process.
    • Targeted Promotions:
      • Offer special promotions for orders above $20 to boost the proportion of high-value orders.

  5. Expand and Refine Partnerships

    • Restaurant Selection:
      • Focus on partnering with restaurants that have high customer satisfaction and can handle increased order volumes efficiently.
    • Quality Assurance:
      • Regularly assess restaurant performance and provide support to maintain high service standards.

  6. Enhance Customer Experience

    • Personalized Recommendations:
      • Utilize customer order history to provide personalized food and restaurant recommendations.
    • Loyalty Programs:
      • Implement a tiered loyalty program to reward frequent customers, encouraging repeat business.

  7. Address Long Delivery Times

    • Process Improvement:
      • Investigate the root causes of orders exceeding 60 minutes and implement solutions to minimize delays.
    • Customer Communication:
      • Keep customers informed about expected delivery times, especially if delays are anticipated.
